%N A121228 Number of ways to write the numbers 1 through 3n on the faces of three n-sided dice, so that the 1st die beats the 2nd with probability > 1/2, the 2nd beats the 3rd with probability > 1/2 and the 3rd beats the 1st with probability > 1/2, and the first die contains the number 1.
%C A121228 From _Lael Lima_, Dec 02 2025: (Start)
%C A121228 A triple of dice satisfying the condition of the description is often called "intransitive" or "nontransitive", referring to the nontransitive relation in which one die can be "better" than another.
%C A121228 If there is no restriction on which die contains the number 1, then the total number of triples of intransitive dice is 3*a(n), corresponding to the cyclic permutations.
%C A121228 Take any m-sided triple of intransitive dice (with 1 contained in the first dice). The (m+n)-sided triple obtained by adjoining the faces of any cyclic permutation of an n-sided triple (after adding 3*m to its entries) is itself intransitive. Hence, the sequence satisfies a(m+n) >= 3*a(m)*a(n), for every m, n > 0. Equivalently, the sequence [3*a(n)] is supermultiplicative.
%C A121228 a(n) = o((3n-1)!/(n!*n!*(n-1)!)) = o((27^n)/n), hence the probability that a random triple is intransitive goes to 0.
%C A121228 log(a(n))/n ~ 3*log(3). Heuristically, the probability of drawing an intransitive triple slowly decays to 0. (End)
%D A121228 M. Gardner, "Mathematical Games: The Paradox of the Nontransitive Dice and the Elusive Principle of Indifference." Sci. Amer. 223, 110-114, Dec. 1970.
